# AINE — Specification-Driven Development Standard

Project-agnostic methodology for AI-native engineering. This rule defines how specifications drive every phase of development — from requirements to deployment. It layers on top of the Gunawan engineering standards (`swe-gunawan-v1`) and governance (`swe-gunawan-governance-v1`) rules.

## 1. Specification-First Principle

The specification is the source of truth — not the code.

- Never write code without a spec section to reference
- When code and spec disagree, the spec wins and the code must be updated
- Every prompt to the AI agent should reference the relevant spec section
- Specs live in `specs/[module-name].md` (or the project's established spec location)
- Use the DICE format for all feature specifications

If no spec exists for the requested work, **stop and write one first** (or ask the SA to write one). Do not generate code from verbal descriptions or chat-only context.

## 2. DICE Specification Format

Every feature spec follows the DICE structure. Each letter maps to a section the AI agent references during code generation:

| Section | Name | What It Contains | Who Writes It | Who Consumes It |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| **D** | Data Model | Entity tables, field types, constraints, relationships, audit columns | SA | Backend Dev, QC |
| **I** | Interface Contract | API endpoints — routes, auth, request/response shapes, status codes, errors | SA | Backend Dev, Frontend Dev |
| **C** | Constraints & Business Rules | Numbered rules governing behavior, sequencing, permissions, state transitions | SA | All roles |
| **E** | Evidence (Acceptance Criteria) | Testable Given/When/Then statements — each becomes a test case | SA, QC | QC, All roles |

### How to reference spec sections

When prompting the AI agent or writing code, always cite the spec section:

```
"Based on spec section D (User Profile entity), generate the migration..."
"Implement the POST /orders endpoint as defined in spec section I..."
"The business rule in C-3 says approval is required before update..."
"Write tests for acceptance criteria E-1 through E-5..."
```

### Reading a DICE spec

Before implementing anything, the agent must read the full spec and confirm:

1. All entities in Section D have primary keys, audit columns (`created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by`), and relationship keys
2. All endpoints in Section I have auth requirements, input validation rules, and error responses
3. All constraints in Section C are numbered and unambiguous
4. All criteria in Section E are independently testable (Given/When/Then)

If any section is incomplete, vague, or missing — **stop and flag it** before writing code.

## 3. Development Stage Workflow

Every feature follows this 10-stage pipeline. Each stage has a corresponding Cursor prompt in `.cursor/prompts/`.

```
[1] Requirements ──→ [2] Task Planning ──→ [3] Database ──→ [4] API Endpoint
                                                                    │
[8] Spec Review ←── [7] Fix Error ←── [6] Test Cases ←── [5] Frontend UI
         │
         ├──→ [9] Impact Check (before any change to existing code)
         └──→ [10] AGENTS.md Update (after patterns stabilize)
```

| Stage | Prompt File | Input | Output | Primary Role |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1. Requirements | `requirements.md` | Business requirement | DICE specification | SA |
| 2. Task Planning | `task-planning.md` | DICE spec | Dependency-ordered task list | SA |
| 3. Database | `database.md` | Spec Section D | Migration script | Backend Dev |
| 4. API Endpoint | `api-endpoint.md` | Spec Section I | Endpoint implementation | Backend Dev |
| 5. Frontend UI | `frontend-ui.md` | Spec Sections I + E | Component code (all 4 states) | Frontend Dev |
| 6. Test Cases | `test-cases.md` | Spec Section E | Test suite | QC |
| 7. Fix Error | `fix-error.md` | Error + spec context | Corrected code | Anyone |
| 8. Spec Review | `spec-review.md` | Complete spec | Gap analysis | QC / SA |
| 9. Impact Check | `impact-check.md` | File or entity name | Dependency report | Anyone |
| 10. AGENTS.md Update | `agents-update.md` | Observed patterns | Updated AGENTS.md | SA / Dev |

### Stage rules

- Stages 1-2 must complete before stages 3-5 begin
- Stages 3 (Database) and 5 (Frontend UI) can run in parallel once the spec is finalized
- Stage 6 (Test Cases) can begin as soon as Section E is written — it does not depend on implementation
- Stage 7 (Fix Error) is used at any time during or after implementation
- Stages 8-10 are continuous improvement — run them periodically, not just once

## 4. Role Responsibilities

Roles define who owns each stage. The AI agent adapts its output based on the active role.

| Role | Owns Stages | Key Responsibilities |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Solution Architect (SA)** | 1, 2, 8, 10 | Write specs, plan tasks, review for completeness, maintain AGENTS.md |
| **Backend Developer** | 3, 4 | Database schema, API endpoints, business logic, input validation |
| **Frontend Developer** | 5 | UI components, state management, API integration, all 4 UI states |
| **Quality Control (QC)** | 6, 8 | Write test cases from acceptance criteria, review specs for testability |
| **Anyone** | 7, 9 | Fix errors (with spec reference), check impact before changes |

