## 5. Spec-Code Traceability

Every code artifact must be traceable back to a spec section. This enables the AI agent (and human reviewers) to verify that what was built matches what was specified.

### Traceability rules

- When generating code, the AI agent must state which spec section it is implementing
- Database migrations trace to Section D
- API endpoints trace to Section I
- Business logic traces to Section C (specific rule numbers)
- Test cases trace to Section E (specific criteria numbers)
- UI components trace to the UI states defined in Section I or E

### Example traceability output

When the AI agent generates code, it should produce output like:

```
Implementing: POST /api/orders
Spec reference: Section I — POST /orders
Auth: Requires SHIP_OWNER role (Section C, Rule 2)
Validation: Required fields — vessel_id, port_id, requested_date (Section I)
Business rule: Auto-approve if vessel has valid schedule (Section C, Rule 5)
Tests needed: E-3, E-4, E-7 (Section E)
```

## 6. UI State Coverage

Every UI component that displays data must handle exactly 4 states. These states must be defined in the spec (Section I or E) and implemented in the component.

| State | What It Shows | When It Applies |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Loading** | Skeleton, spinner, or placeholder | Data is being fetched |
| **Error** | Error message with retry action | Fetch failed or business rule violation |
| **Empty** | Contextual empty message with action | Fetch succeeded but returned no data |
| **Success** | Actual data rendered | Fetch succeeded with data |

### Rules

- The spec must define what each state looks like for every data-driven component
- The AI agent must implement all 4 states — no component may assume data is always present
- Error states must show user-friendly messages, never raw error objects
- Empty states should guide the user toward an action (e.g., "No orders yet. Create your first order.")
- Loading states should match the layout of the success state (skeleton screens preferred over spinners)

## 7. Acceptance Criteria as Tests

Every item in Section E (Evidence) of the spec becomes a test case. This is not optional — it is the contract between the spec and the implementation.

### Rules

- Each Given/When/Then criterion maps to exactly one test case
- Test case names must reference the criterion number: `E-1: Given a logged-in user, when they view their profile...`
- The normal case (happy path) is always tested first
- Each endpoint must have at least 3 edge-case tests beyond the normal case
- A feature is not done until every acceptance criterion has a passing test

### Test coverage mapping

```
Spec Section E                    Test Suite
─────────────                     ──────────
E-1: Given ... when ... then ...  → test('E-1: ...')
E-2: Given ... when ... then ...  → test('E-2: ...')
E-3: Given ... when ... then ...  → test('E-3: ...')
...
```

