## 8. Spec Completeness Checklist

Before any implementation begins, the spec must pass this checklist. The AI agent should run this check when asked to implement a feature.

### Section D — Data Model
- [ ] Every entity has a primary key (UUID preferred)
- [ ] Every entity has `created_at`, `updated_at`, `created_by` audit columns
- [ ] All foreign key relationships are explicitly defined
- [ ] Field types and constraints (required, unique, max length) are specified
- [ ] Indexes are identified for frequently queried columns

### Section I — Interface Contract
- [ ] Every endpoint has an HTTP method and path
- [ ] Auth requirements are specified (which roles can call it)
- [ ] Request body / query params are fully typed with required/optional markers
- [ ] Success response shape is defined with status code
- [ ] All error responses are listed (401, 403, 404, 400, 409, 500)

### Section C — Constraints & Business Rules
- [ ] Every rule is numbered (C-1, C-2, ...)
- [ ] Rules are unambiguous — no "should" or "might", only "must" or "must not"
- [ ] State transitions are explicit (what triggers them, what blocks them)
- [ ] Permission rules reference specific roles from the Roles table

### Section E — Evidence (Acceptance Criteria)
- [ ] Every criterion is numbered (E-1, E-2, ...)
- [ ] Every criterion follows Given/When/Then format
- [ ] Every criterion is independently testable
- [ ] Normal case is covered
- [ ] At least 3 edge cases per endpoint are covered
- [ ] Error scenarios (wrong role, missing field, invalid state) are covered

If any item fails, the spec is incomplete. Flag it to the SA before proceeding.

